{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}} {{Use British English|date=February 2015}}
The '''National Admissions Test for Law''', or '''LNAT''', is an admissions aptitude test that was adopted in 2004 by eight [[United Kingdom|UK]] [[university]] law programmes<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/3451897.stm Education: New entry test for law students], [[BBC News]], UK.</ref> as an admissions requirement for home applicants. The test was established at the leading urgency of [[Oxford University]] as an answer to the problem facing universities trying to select from an increasingly competitive pool with similarly high [[Advanced Level (UK)|A-levels]]. With effect from its second year, the LNAT is required for UK and overseas applicants alike. There are now nine participating law schools and hundreds of test centres worldwide.
==Format== The LNAT is 135 minutes long and consists of two sections. The test taker is allotted 40 minutes to complete the essay and 95 minutes to answer 42 multiple-choice questions aimed at measuring reading comprehension and logical reasoning skills. The reading portion contains twelve short passages, with three or four questions about each passage. The questions typically ask for terms and arguments from the reading to be defined by inference. The essay portion is 40 minutes long and involves the candidate answering one of three available essay questions. The questions are generally open-ended prompts that can focus on any one of a wide variety of issues.<ref name="LNAT Format">{{cite web | url=http://www.lnat.ac.uk/what-is-lnat/test-format/ | title=Test format – LNAT | publisher=LNAT Consortium Ltd | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref>
The reading section is scored out of 42 and the essays are individually marked by [[proctor]]s at the respective universities.
The universities currently using the LNAT are:<ref name="Why Join LNAT">{{cite web | url=http://www.lnat.ac.uk/why-join-lnat/ | title=Why join LNAT? | publisher=LNAT Consortium Ltd | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref>
*[[University of Bristol]]<ref name="Bristol">{{cite web | url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/law/study/ugdegrees/ugadmissions/ug-admissions-faq.html | title=LNAT FAQs – University of Bristol Law School | publisher=[[University of Bristol]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916092509/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/law/study/ugdegrees/ugadmissions/ug-admissions-faq.html | archivedate=16 September 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> *[[Durham University]]<ref name="Durham">{{cite web | url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/law/undergraduate/lnat/ | title=Durham Law School: LNAT | publisher=[[Durham University]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> *[[University of Glasgow]]<ref name="Glasgow">{{cite web | url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/undergraduate/degrees/law/#/entryrequirements | title=Law – Undergraduate Degree Programmes | publisher=[[University of Glasgow]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> *[[King's College London]]<ref name="KCL">{{cite web | url=http://www.kcl.ac.uk/study/undergraduate/courses/law-llb.aspx | title=Law LLB | publisher=[[King's College London]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> *[[University of Nottingham]]<ref name="Nottingham">{{cite web | url=http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/ugstudy/courses/law/llb-law.aspx | title=Law LLB | publisher=[[University of Nottingham]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> *[[University of Oxford]]<ref name="Oxford">{{cite web | url=https://www.ox.ac.uk/admissions/undergraduate/applying-to-oxford/tests?wssl=1 | title=Tests | publisher=[[University of Oxford]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> *[[SOAS School of Law]], [[University of London]] (for students with only BTEC qualifications)<ref name="SOAS LLB">{{cite web | url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/law/programmes/llblaw/ | title=LLB Law Single Honours at SOAS University of London | publisher=[[University of London]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name="SOAS BA">{{cite web | url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/law/programmes/balawand/ | title=BA Law and... Combined Honours Degree at SOAS University of London | publisher=[[University of London]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> *[[University College London]]<ref name="UCL">{{cite web | url=http://www.laws.ucl.ac.uk/study/undergraduate/applying/national-admission-test-law-lnat/ | title=National Admission Test for Law (LNAT) – UCL Faculty of Laws | publisher=[[University College London]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> *[[NUI Maynooth]] (mature entry only){{citation needed|date=September 2016}} *[[IE University]], Spain<ref name="IE University">{{cite web | url=http://www.ie.edu/university/admission/admission-process/admissions-test/ | title=Admissions Test | publisher=[[IE University]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> *[[Singapore University of Social Sciences]], Singapore<ref name="SIM LLB">{{cite web | url=http://www.unisim.edu.sg/programmes/programme-details/Pages/Bachelor-of-Laws.aspx | title=Bachelor of Laws | publisher=[[Singapore University of Social Sciences]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name="SIM JD">{{cite web | url=http://www.unisim.edu.sg/programmes/programme-details/Pages/Juris-Doctor.aspx | title=Juris Doctor | publisher=[[SIM University]] | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> * [[London School of Economics]]
==Results== The LNAT was first administered on 3 November 2004.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} The average score for the reading portion was 13.16 out of 24. Four test-takers received a 21 out of 24, the highest score achieved;<ref name="Guardian 2005">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2005/feb/03/highereducation.accesstouniversity | title=Pupils achieve 'same marks' in law admission tests | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=February 3, 2005 | accessdate=September 10, 2016 | author=Ford, Liz}}</ref> the lowest score achieved by the 4,345 candidates was 3.<ref name="BBC 2005">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/education/4230881.stm | title=Law candidates 'not good enough' | work=[[BBC News]] | date=February 3, 2005 | accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> Men performed slightly better than women on the multiple-choice portion, scoring 13.37 and 13.02 on average, respectively.<ref name="BBC 2005" /> A [[University of Bristol]] report on the scores expressed dissatisfaction with the ability of law candidates to develop "reasoned arguments".<ref name="BBC 2005" /> Men and women scored approximately equally to each other, in contrast to the distribution of A grades in A-level law, which were awarded to 19.3% of women and only 14.1% of men.<ref name="BBC 2005" />
The LNAT consortium also reported statistically insignificant differences in scores between state and independent students.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} Research conducted by the University of Bristol concluded: "the impact of the Lnat both in general and on specific supposedly sensitive [[widening participation]] groups has been negligible".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lnat.ac.uk/2010/documents/pressrelease0908.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-07 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815232655/http://www.lnat.ac.uk/2010/documents/pressrelease0908.pdf |archivedate=15 August 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}
